sentences: Jennifer Helen McLeod  (born 12 November 1941) is a New Zealand composer and former professor of music at Victoria University of Wellington.

Born in Wellington, McLeod graduated BMus (Hons) from Victoria University in 1964, and the same year a New Zealand government bursary enabled her to study for two years in Europe with Messiaen, Stockhausen and Berio.
In 1967 she became a lecturer in music at Victoria University, and Professor in 1971, a position she held until 1976.

sentences: The Rock Concerto began life in 1986 as a (first) Rock Sonata for piano, a work with strong classical roots and in places of Lisztian difficulty, commissioned by the New Zealand pianist Bruce Greenfield for his gifted virtuoso pupil the seventeen-year-old Eugene Albulescu.

(Partly on the strength of this score, the composer was invited in 1987 as an international guest composer to a ten-day contemporary music festival in Kentucky, hosted by the Louisville Orchestra for its fortieth anniversary.)
At Albulescu’s request, in 2009 she scored and revised the rock sonata as a piano concerto which he might also direct from the keyboard.
The New Zealand International Arts Festival premiered McLeod's opera Hohepa in 2012.

Photo of Jenny McLeod, 1976
Several of Jenny McLeod's songs were written for a "Sun Festival" in Wellington Harbour in the mid 1980s.

Born in Wellington, McLeod graduated BMus (Hons) from Victoria University in 1964, and the same year a New Zealand government bursary enabled her to study for two years in Europe with Messiaen, Stockhausen and Berio.
She is best known for two major works, Earth and Sky and Under the Sun for large forces.
Under the Sun ===
Under the Sun was commissioned by the city of Palmerston North (Manawatu, New Zealand) to commemorate its centenary.
It was performed six times there on the week of 24–30 May 1971.
It tells the history of the Sun, from the formation of the earth through the entire span of life on earth till the Sun cools.
The production involved 1000 people and took two years to bring to performance.
